# Business Model Canvas

## Customer Segments
- University students, currently studying an undergraduate degree, between 17-24 years of age. Postgraduates and those in further study may be surveyed, but are required to tell their experience from when being a first year student. 
- This is to collect further data in the difficulties of the enrollment system for first year students, and to understand EAIT students' consensus on our solution.

## Value Propositions
- Accepted hypothesis displays interviewees have a need for an ease of access to information in a more uniform, simpler model. 
- Display transparently all prerequisites for all courses a student may take.
- Surface elective courses aligned with a student's stated academic interests and areas of focus.
- Enable students to submit and share their recommended course selection based on personal academic experience.
- Display the most common course progression pathway taken by students within the same degree program.
## Channels
- Integrate software by embedding it within existing UQ and SI-net web infrastructure to ensure seamless student access.

## Customer Relationships
- Students interact with the system autonomously, with access to a formal support channel for technical issues and enquiries

## Revenue Streams
- Recurring annual fees covering software licensing, maintenance, and continued operational support.

## Accepted Hypothesis: 
- We believe that students consistently lack accessible, consolidated course information at the point of enrolment; impending informed academic planning and leading to inconvenient and unclear decision making.

## Refuted Hypothesis:
- (Technically proven true, but lacking in specifity)
- We believe that a major and surprisingly common pain point UQ students regarding the UQ enrolment system is the lack of context and information when selecting courses, or at least a lack of convenience and clarity when looking up the appropriate sources.